		       @{ " Read here first!!" LINK "details" }

This guide explains how to connect standard SCSI II devices to
the BlizzardPPC in a 1200 Tower and how to build a proper
cable to do it.

From some days I'm finally a satisfied Power user, I bought a
BlizzardPPC with 040/603@240 with SCSI, and, I have to tell,
it's a wonderful product, the board layout is incredible, and
the speed of the little PPC too. The only thing I had to be
critical with, is the supplied SCSI cable. The BlizzardPPC+
comes with a scsi cable designed for desktop 1200s, it has a
normal ext.SCSI connector who fits the hole in the rear of the
Amiga 1200 desktop case. On that port you can easily add an
external scsi cabinet and feel the power of a good fast scsi
controller. But I have an Ateo tower for my 1200, and some
internal scsi devices (HD and CD-Rom) bought just before the
Blizzard. You can put the external connector on the rear of
tower, in the cutout, but doing this you lose the possibility
to mount internal devices. So I took the cable of the Blizzard
and drived in all my big city to find out a sort of adapter, or
something like it. It has been impossible. The connector on the
Blizzard is too little, I couldn't find any right cable/connector. The
only solution proposed by a shop was to buy a cable for the external
port, an adapter to SCSI-I, and then a cable to adapt the internal
SCSI chain cable. It would represent a big MESS in the tower with the
cables, and a quite expensive solution (about 120 DM). So I decided
to build a cable. Before going on, read the @{ "disclaimer" LINK "disclaimer"}
Please note that to do this, you have to cut the original cable of
the BlizzardPPC.

