@NODE "Needs" "What you need"

Ok,let`s see what we`ll need...

-First, a good pair of little scissors, the littler and sharper,
the better you go.

- a normal SCSI internal cable for scsi chains, with AT LEAST 4
connectors, better if they have 5 connectors. The connectors must be
standard scsi 50pins female ones.

- 2 male scsi connectors. These connectors have to be of the type
that when you put the cable in them you only have to press on them
to mount.(sorry, I don't know the english word :P)

- A LOT o patience.

- not really needed, but a little screwdriver with a flat head
is welcome

@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mounting" "Ok,let`s go!!!"

The first thing that you have to do is sad: you have to cut the cable
that came with the board exactly in the middle. Now you have two little
cables, one with the plug that goes on the Blizzard, and another with
the external scsi port. Take the first one.

The cable is made of 50 wires, with the scissors separe every
wire, doing cuts of about 2-3 CMs. Make sure that every wire is 
now separed by each other. This phase is quite delicate, you have
to pay very much attention, if you do a wrong cut and cut also
one single wire, you have to do everything again, hoping that the cable
will be long enough. This took to me half a hour, so be patient.


Then plug the male scsi connector in the first female of the scsi chain
cable, just to check wich side the pin#1 will be. Then put the male
connector on your desk (maybe you may want to ensure it with some tape).
Open the connector and plug every single cable in the metallic "V" pins.
This will take some time, be patient and double check that you plug
the wires in the right order. Look at @{ " schemes " SYSTEM "sys:utilities/multiview schemes.iff" } to see how to plug
the wires. Double check again if every wire is on the right order!
Eventually do this with the help of a little screwdriver, that may be
useful to fix the little wires in the "V" pins.
Now close the connector, and push strongly to fix it. Now half the work
is done. Put this male connector in the first female of the scsi cable.

Now take the other part of the cable that arrived with the BlizzardPPC.
You have to do exactly the same thing that you did for the first, separe
the wires, plug them in the V pins in the connector, close the connector etc.
This male connector has to be placed in the LAST connector in the scsi chain
cable.
Unscrew the metal plate where the ports is screwed, this is for the desktop
1200s. now screw the port in the rear of the tower (the Ateo tower has a
cutout for it, for the Micronik tower is available a special cutout). Now
your scsi cable should look just like this:


BlizzardPPC                                              ext scsi port
    |                                                 (rear of the tower)
    |-------||----------|--------|-------|---------||-------<>
           Modify      scsi     scsi    scsi      Modify
                      device   device  device

Now you can plug your SCSI devices directly in the standard scsi
connectors, and you don't miss the possibility to use external
scsi devices (like scanners etc.).

Ok, you did your cable. WELL DONE!
Now don't forget to thank me :)

